<b>Avtar Singh Atwal</b> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../008/11008.xml">
23 February</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../630/34630.xml">
1943</link> - <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../733/2733.xml">
25 April</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../755/34755.xml">
1983</link>) was a senior <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../533/14533.xml">
India</link></country>
n police officer. He was an <work wordnetid="100575741" confidence="0.8">
<administrative_unit wordnetid="108077292" confidence="0.8">
<event wordnetid="100029378" confidence="0.8">
<service wordnetid="100577525" confidence="0.8">
<agency wordnetid="108337324" confidence="0.8">
<act wordnetid="100030358" confidence="0.8">
<psychological_feature wordnetid="100023100" confidence="0.8">
<activity wordnetid="100407535" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../884/451884.xml">
IPS</link></activity>
</psychological_feature>
</act>
</agency>
</service>
</event>
</administrative_unit>
</work>
, which he joined after serving five years as an Emergency Commissioned Officer in the Regiment of Artillery. He was serving as Deputy Inspector General of Police of Jalandhar District in <region wordnetid="108630985" confidence="0.8">
<region wordnetid="108630039" confidence="0.8">
<administrative_district wordnetid="108491826" confidence="0.8">
<location wordnetid="100027167" confidence="0.8">
<district wordnetid="108552138" confidence="0.8">
<country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../559/2353559.xml">
Punjab</link></country>
</district>
</location>
</administrative_district>
</region>
</region>
. He was shot from behind and killed on 25 April 1983 by militants when he was coming out of <building wordnetid="102913152" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../823/5723823.xml">
Golden Temple</link></building>
 after paying obeisance and with Karah Prasaad in his hands. He was unarmed.<weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://books.google.com/books?id=oA_7jvsaBzYC&amp;pg=PA89&amp;lpg=PA89&amp;dq=atwal+police+golden+temple&amp;source=web&amp;ots=dIyRKY5_Ei&amp;sig=RSnM93ZV6Iwc8QSKJy9ptEzHd1g#PPA90,M1">
http://books.google.com/books?id=oA_7jvsaBzYC&amp;pg=PA89&amp;lpg=PA89&amp;dq=atwal+police+golden+temple&amp;source=web&amp;ots=dIyRKY5_Ei&amp;sig=RSnM93ZV6Iwc8QSKJy9ptEzHd1g#PPA90,M1</weblink></p>
<p>

He was awarded President Police Medal for Gallantry posthumously.<weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://punjabpolice.org/MARTYR/index.html">
http://punjabpolice.org/MARTYR/index.html</weblink>He was survived by his wife and son. His wife Amrita Atwal later joined the Punjab Civil Services and thereafter was seconded to the IAS before her retirement. His son, Harbir Atwal also joined the Punjab Police as an Inspector and was awarded the "Sword of Honour" during the Passing Out Parade. </p>

